WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:02.170
&gt;&gt; Guy Lamolinara:
Good morning everybody,

00:00:02.170 --> 00:00:04.940
so glad to see you all
here and thanks for coming

00:00:04.940 --> 00:00:07.260
to the National Book Festival.

00:00:07.260 --> 00:00:10.750
I'm Guy Lamolinara and I work
at the Library of Congress

00:00:10.750 --> 00:00:14.410
in a Division appropriately
called the Center for the Book.

00:00:14.410 --> 00:00:15.720
All day here at the Library

00:00:15.720 --> 00:00:18.920
of Congress National Book
Festival we are recognizing

00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:21.160
and celebrating the
importance of reading

00:00:21.160 --> 00:00:23.280
and authors and books.

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:25.350
The Library of Congress
makes it seem easy

00:00:25.350 --> 00:00:27.680
to do this each and every year.

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:30.590
But the truth is the National
Festival, Book Festival,

00:00:30.590 --> 00:00:32.620
is a huge undertaking.

00:00:32.620 --> 00:00:35.600
It is a huge financial
undertaking but it is free

00:00:35.600 --> 00:00:37.120
for everyone thanks

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:40.720
to our generous supporters
and sponsors.

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:42.020
Spread the joy of reading

00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:45.880
with your gift online
at loc.gov/donate.

00:00:45.880 --> 00:00:48.710
You can do that from the
festival lab or you can do it

00:00:48.710 --> 00:00:50.630
when you purchase books today.

00:00:50.630 --> 00:00:53.870
And now on to our main event.

00:00:53.870 --> 00:00:56.230
David Ezra Stein is a creator

00:00:56.230 --> 00:00:59.900
of many award winning picture
books including Interrupting

00:00:59.900 --> 00:01:02.270
Chicken and the Elephant
of Surprise,

00:01:02.270 --> 00:01:06.390
which was awarded a Caldecott
Honor as well as Ice Boy,

00:01:06.390 --> 00:01:11.770
Because Amelia Smiled, Dinosaur
Kisses and I'm My Own Dog.

00:01:11.770 --> 00:01:16.510
David received the Ezra Jack
Keats new writer award in 2008.

00:01:16.510 --> 00:01:18.790
And his books have
received numerous awards

00:01:18.790 --> 00:01:20.090
and have been named to many,

00:01:20.090 --> 00:01:22.880
many book lists including
Publisher's Weekly,

00:01:22.880 --> 00:01:25.120
Best Children's Books
of the Year

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:28.770
and School Library Journal
Best Books of the Year.

00:01:28.770 --> 00:01:31.440
David is a graduate of the
Parson's School of Design

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:33.090
in New York where he studied

00:01:33.090 --> 00:01:36.240
under author/illustrator
Pat Cummings.

00:01:36.240 --> 00:01:37.660
David has worked in many,

00:01:37.660 --> 00:01:41.400
many fields as a window
display artist, as a puppeteer

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:45.770
and puppet builder, an interior
and set design illustrator.

00:01:45.770 --> 00:01:48.560
He's done cartoons for
the New Yorker Magazine.

00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:50.870
And his books have
been translated

00:01:50.870 --> 00:01:54.290
into so many languages I can
hardly tell you, Chinese,

00:01:54.290 --> 00:01:59.680
Korean, Japanese, Spanish,
Catalan, French and Finnish.

00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:02.440
David was born in Brooklyn,
New York and he lives

00:02:02.440 --> 00:02:04.970
with his family in
Kew Gardens, New York.

00:02:04.970 --> 00:02:07.230
Please welcome David Ezra Stein.

00:02:07.230 --> 00:02:08.530
[applause]

00:02:08.530 --> 00:02:09.830
&gt;&gt; David Ezra Stein:
Hey everybody.

00:02:09.830 --> 00:02:11.130
Thank you, Guy.

00:02:11.130 --> 00:02:15.860
[applause] It's nice to be back
at the National Book Festival.

00:02:15.860 --> 00:02:19.230
I was here when my first
chicken book came out,

00:02:19.230 --> 00:02:21.030
Interrupting Chicken.

00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:23.660
That was some years ago
and that was a lot of fun.

00:02:23.660 --> 00:02:27.570
So I'm looking forward to
celebrating this new book,

00:02:27.570 --> 00:02:31.280
Interrupting Chicken and
the Elephant of Surprise.

00:02:31.280 --> 00:02:35.120
So we're going to read
the story together.

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:38.640
I'm going to get kind of messy
and do some painting up here.

00:02:38.640 --> 00:02:41.260
Maybe you've seen people
drawing but I don't know

00:02:41.260 --> 00:02:44.200
if you've seen anybody
using acrylic paint up here.

00:02:44.200 --> 00:02:47.320
We're going to get
colorful and messy.

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:50.850
So how's your summer
going, everybody?

00:02:50.850 --> 00:02:52.150
It's the end of the summer.

00:02:52.150 --> 00:02:54.050
You guys having a good time?

00:02:54.050 --> 00:02:55.350
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:02:55.350 --> 00:02:56.650
&gt;&gt; David Ezra Stein:
Is anybody back

00:02:56.650 --> 00:02:57.950
in school yet, back in school?

00:02:57.950 --> 00:02:59.250
Oh man, ok.

00:02:59.250 --> 00:03:00.550
Well that's exciting.

00:03:00.550 --> 00:03:03.190
Anybody just started
kindergarten?

00:03:03.190 --> 00:03:06.390
Yeah, wow.

00:03:06.390 --> 00:03:07.980
My daughter is five and she's

00:03:07.980 --> 00:03:11.490
about to start kindergarten
next week.

00:03:11.490 --> 00:03:15.160
So I am probably more
nervous than she is

00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:18.170
so I'm not really
showing that to her.

00:03:18.170 --> 00:03:19.630
I'm trying to keep
that to myself.

00:03:19.630 --> 00:03:22.730
But I think she's going
to have a good time.

00:03:22.730 --> 00:03:25.240
But when I, you know, when
I was in kindergarten that's

00:03:25.240 --> 00:03:26.820
when I learned to read.

00:03:26.820 --> 00:03:29.480
And it was already halfway

00:03:29.480 --> 00:03:32.390
through kindergarten
before I knew how to read

00:03:32.390 --> 00:03:35.950
and I remember trying to read
a book over the winter break

00:03:35.950 --> 00:03:39.900
and it was about a moose who
finds an egg and he tries

00:03:39.900 --> 00:03:42.560
to raise it until it hatches.

00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:44.730
And I was reading the whole book

00:03:44.730 --> 00:03:47.750
but there was this one
word I couldn't get.

00:03:47.750 --> 00:03:49.050
I just couldn't figure it out.

00:03:49.050 --> 00:03:50.350
It was too complicated.

00:03:50.350 --> 00:03:54.360
It started with a Ch and I
just couldn't figure it out.

00:03:54.360 --> 00:03:56.410
It had all these letters in it.

00:03:56.410 --> 00:04:01.470
The last letter was an n. Can
anybody guess what the word was

00:04:01.470 --> 00:04:03.510
that I couldn't read?

00:04:03.510 --> 00:04:06.530
Yeah, I could not read
this word chicken,

00:04:06.530 --> 00:04:09.440
actually it was chickens
because the chickens come back

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:12.190
to get their egg from
the moose at the end,

00:04:12.190 --> 00:04:13.490
I think that was how it went.

00:04:13.490 --> 00:04:16.170
It's been a long time
since I read that book.

00:04:16.170 --> 00:04:19.160
So I finally just memorized the
word chickens and when I got

00:04:19.160 --> 00:04:22.390
to the part of the book that
said chickens I said chickens.

00:04:22.390 --> 00:04:26.300
And then I knew how to
read and it was fantastic.

00:04:26.300 --> 00:04:30.460
And I could go to my school
library, I was very lucky to go

00:04:30.460 --> 00:04:34.170
to my school library and just
walk in and nobody bothered me.

00:04:34.170 --> 00:04:37.960
I could just go take a book,
whatever book looked interesting

00:04:37.960 --> 00:04:41.260
to me, and just read it and
nobody asked any questions,

00:04:41.260 --> 00:04:44.230
as far as I remember, it
was just me and the book.

00:04:44.230 --> 00:04:46.370
And so I wish that for
all of you and I hope

00:04:46.370 --> 00:04:49.730
that you have a great time
in your school library

00:04:49.730 --> 00:04:51.960
and reading with your parents.

00:04:51.960 --> 00:04:55.460
So I'd like to read you
Interrupting Chicken

00:04:55.460 --> 00:05:02.950
and the Elephant of Surprise
by David Ezra Stein, me.

00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:08.230
[laughter] Ok so the cover
says Interrupting Chicken

00:05:08.230 --> 00:05:11.750
and the Elephant of
Surprise, what a surprise.

00:05:11.750 --> 00:05:14.270
Chicken, there are no
elephants in this book.

00:05:14.270 --> 00:05:17.300
And then see in the
corner there?

00:05:17.300 --> 00:05:22.350
Who's that little guy
going hee, hee, hee, hee?

00:05:22.350 --> 00:05:24.970
An elephant.

00:05:24.970 --> 00:05:26.780
Wow this works, ok.

00:05:26.780 --> 00:05:30.170
Let's see, so Interrupting
Chicken

00:05:30.170 --> 00:05:32.010
and the Elephant of Surprise.

00:05:32.010 --> 00:05:35.720
Interrupting Chicken
and the Elephant

00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:37.700
of Surprise, I said
that already.

00:05:37.700 --> 00:05:43.350
Oh man but anyway you can see
that this is the chicken's home,

00:05:43.350 --> 00:05:46.970
her porch and then you can
see the school bus coming

00:05:46.970 --> 00:05:49.660
to drop her off, right?

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:51.620
And all the interesting
things that you can look

00:05:51.620 --> 00:05:56.160
at when you look at the book.

00:05:56.160 --> 00:06:01.520
It was after school for
the little red chicken.

00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:02.820
Well chicken, said poppa,

00:06:02.820 --> 00:06:05.370
did you have a good
day at school today?

00:06:05.370 --> 00:06:09.660
Yes, poppa, and today my teacher
told us every story has an

00:06:09.660 --> 00:06:12.450
elephant of surprise.

00:06:12.450 --> 00:06:15.960
So let's read a story and
we'll find the elephant.

00:06:15.960 --> 00:06:18.540
Chicken, she wasn't
talking about an elephant,

00:06:18.540 --> 00:06:21.730
she was talking about
an element of surprise.

00:06:21.730 --> 00:06:24.230
What's an element of surprise?

00:06:24.230 --> 00:06:28.200
It's the part of the story that
makes you say woe, I didn't know

00:06:28.200 --> 00:06:31.550
that was going to
happen, said poppa.

00:06:31.550 --> 00:06:35.810
An elephant in a story
always makes me say woe.

00:06:35.810 --> 00:06:39.160
So please let's read
a story together.

00:06:39.160 --> 00:06:42.020
Alright fine but I don't expect
you'll find any elephants

00:06:42.020 --> 00:06:44.660
in this story.

00:06:44.660 --> 00:06:49.070
The ugly duckling, oh man this
is going to be tough to read.

00:06:49.070 --> 00:06:50.740
[laughter] I think
my eyes are dried up.

00:06:50.740 --> 00:06:52.700
Ok, after a long, lonely winter

00:06:52.700 --> 00:06:56.200
in the cave the ugly duckling
was growing desperate.

00:06:56.200 --> 00:06:58.500
I don't care if they
tear me to pieces.

00:06:58.500 --> 00:07:02.730
I must be near those glorious
creatures for just one moment,

00:07:02.730 --> 00:07:07.220
he said, as he flung himself
toward the flock of swans.

00:07:07.220 --> 00:07:10.570
To his amazement the
graceful birds did not attack

00:07:10.570 --> 00:07:14.780
or tease him but seemed to
except him as one of their own.

00:07:14.780 --> 00:07:19.740
He peered into the water at his
reflection, gasped and said,

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:21.200
surprise, I'm an elephant.

00:07:21.200 --> 00:07:24.850
Thank you for finding me.

00:07:24.850 --> 00:07:30.300
No problem, we learned
about you in school.

00:07:30.300 --> 00:07:33.830
Chicken, there are no
elephants in the Ugly Duckling.

00:07:33.830 --> 00:07:37.120
Every good story has one,
that's what my teacher said.

00:07:37.120 --> 00:07:39.260
That's ridiculous.

00:07:39.260 --> 00:07:41.460
Is the Ugly Duckling
a good story?

00:07:41.460 --> 00:07:45.980
Well yes but, then it must
have an elephant of surprise.

00:07:45.980 --> 00:07:47.280
Let's try another book.

00:07:47.280 --> 00:07:50.250
Rapunzel, enchanted

00:07:50.250 --> 00:07:58.150
by Rapunzel's beautiful singing
the prince drew near the tower.

00:07:58.150 --> 00:08:00.540
He had waited for this night.

00:08:00.540 --> 00:08:04.400
Rapunzel, Rapunzel, he
called, let down your hair.

00:08:04.400 --> 00:08:08.930
Silently a braid of Rapunzel's
hair slid down the tower wall.

00:08:08.930 --> 00:08:13.890
Come to me my prince, called
a melodious voice above.

00:08:13.890 --> 00:08:16.950
With all haste the
prince began to climb.

00:08:16.950 --> 00:08:20.300
When he reached Rapunzel
he gazed at his love

00:08:20.300 --> 00:08:24.980
and she said surprise,
I'm an elephant.

00:08:24.980 --> 00:08:28.910
[laughter] You've done it again.

00:08:28.910 --> 00:08:31.090
You're welcome.

00:08:31.090 --> 00:08:33.640
Chicken, I know there is
no elephant in Rapunzel,

00:08:33.640 --> 00:08:36.850
that's just plain ludicrous.

00:08:36.850 --> 00:08:39.760
Don't you feel sorry
for the elephant, poppa?

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:43.480
All alone waiting for
someone to find him.

00:08:43.480 --> 00:08:47.210
Read another story and we'll
find the poor elephant.

00:08:47.210 --> 00:08:50.890
Chicken this is silly.

00:08:50.890 --> 00:08:52.190
It's my homework.

00:08:52.190 --> 00:08:54.000
Ms. Gizzard said
to read three books

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:57.990
and find the elephant
in all of them.

00:08:57.990 --> 00:09:03.890
Ok, poppa said, here comes
another story with no elephant.

00:09:03.890 --> 00:09:08.550
The Little Mermaid, already
the mermaid could feel the sea

00:09:08.550 --> 00:09:10.220
which is potent working,

00:09:10.220 --> 00:09:13.980
soon with her new legs she
would dance with the prince

00:09:13.980 --> 00:09:16.370
and he would fall
in love with her.

00:09:16.370 --> 00:09:20.070
As she crawled out of the waves
a sharp pain passed through her.

00:09:20.070 --> 00:09:25.110
She fell to the steps of the
palace and knew only darkness.

00:09:25.110 --> 00:09:28.380
When she woke the prince
himself was standing over her.

00:09:28.380 --> 00:09:32.360
In the moonlight she saw
that her wish had come true.

00:09:32.360 --> 00:09:37.790
She finally did have
legs, elephant legs.

00:09:37.790 --> 00:09:39.630
Wow, that was a surprise.

00:09:39.630 --> 00:09:44.610
I know. Well chicken,
are you happy?

00:09:44.610 --> 00:09:47.720
You put an elephant in every
story but now I'm going

00:09:47.720 --> 00:09:50.370
to tell you a story and
I'll make sure there are

00:09:50.370 --> 00:09:52.220
no elephants.

00:09:52.220 --> 00:09:54.830
Ok poppa and I'll
draw the pictures.

00:09:54.830 --> 00:09:59.140
Poppa's story, by poppa, hi,

00:09:59.140 --> 00:10:04.010
once there was a poppa whose
daughter loved elephants

00:10:04.010 --> 00:10:06.050
and she thought she
saw them everywhere

00:10:06.050 --> 00:10:08.270
but there were no elephants.

00:10:08.270 --> 00:10:09.890
Every day he got her dressed

00:10:09.890 --> 00:10:12.430
but there were no
elephants in the dresser.

00:10:12.430 --> 00:10:14.150
Every day he fixed her breakfast

00:10:14.150 --> 00:10:17.480
but there were no elephants
in the refrigerator.

00:10:17.480 --> 00:10:23.160
And every day he packed
her off to elephant school,

00:10:23.160 --> 00:10:26.510
ta da, hi, hop in chicken.

00:10:26.510 --> 00:10:35.560
[ Crowd noise ]

00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:39.010
Oh poppa, I knew there'd be
an elephant in the story.

00:10:39.010 --> 00:10:42.120
So did I, somehow, said poppa.

00:10:42.120 --> 00:10:44.290
And it was right at the
end, said the chicken.

00:10:44.290 --> 00:10:46.450
What a great surprise.

00:10:46.450 --> 00:10:49.620
Are we done, chicken?

00:10:49.620 --> 00:10:50.920
Yes, poppa.

00:10:50.920 --> 00:10:56.530
Now you can help me
with my math homework.

00:10:56.530 --> 00:10:59.300
Because that's the end
of Interrupting Chicken

00:10:59.300 --> 00:11:02.350
and the Elephant of Surprise.

00:11:02.350 --> 00:11:03.900
[applause] Ta da, thank you.

00:11:03.900 --> 00:11:07.000
So how are we for time?

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.320
Ok good, we have
some time to do,

00:11:09.320 --> 00:11:14.880
I was going to just show you
how I paint an illustration

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:17.750
but I thought maybe I'd
try something a little more

00:11:17.750 --> 00:11:21.500
interesting and try to tell
you a story while I do it

00:11:21.500 --> 00:11:22.800
at the same time.

00:11:22.800 --> 00:11:24.140
So I've never tried this before.

00:11:24.140 --> 00:11:27.040
This is, this may fail.

00:11:27.040 --> 00:11:29.250
Things might blow up.

00:11:29.250 --> 00:11:31.300
I don't know.

00:11:31.300 --> 00:11:32.600
We'll find out.

00:11:32.600 --> 00:11:37.200
But artists like to take
chances and try new things.

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:41.370
